ogimage={srcImage.src}
>
    <div class="text-center">
        <MyH1 text="Best trout fishing spots near Gresham, Oregon" />
        <p class="mb-4">Comprehensive guide to the best trout fishing hotspots – with seasonal tips, gear suggestions, and local insights.</p>

        <Image
            src={srcImage}
            alt="Best trout fishing spots near Gresham, Oregon"
            loading={"eager"}
            fetchpriority={"high"}
            class="rounded-xl shadow mx-auto"
            />
            <br>
    </div>

<h3>
    <strong>1. Mt. Hood Pond (Gresham)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A 5‑acre, heavily stocked rainbow trout pond on the Mt. Hood Community College campus.
    </li>
    <li>
        Stocked in late winter through spring and again in fall, including trophy-sized bows 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Youth-only season</strong>: April–August only youth and disabled anglers may fish, with all-ages allowed in fall and winter 
    </li>
    <li>
        Best fishing: right after stocking, using PowerBait, nightcrawlers, spinners, or spoons&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Salish Ponds (Fairview)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Two connected ponds just 10 min from Gresham, regularly stocked with rainbow trout 
    </li>
    <li>
        Smaller west pond stocked for trout; east pond focuses on warmwater species 
    </li>
    <li>
        Trails, paved bank access — perfect for families and fly/spin anglers&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Blue Lake (Fairview)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A 62‑acre metro lake popular for stocked trout (8–12″) and warmwater species 
    </li>
    <li>
        Full park amenities: boat rentals, docks, trails – fish early spring or late fall for best trout action&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Creeks &amp; Rivers (Eagle Creek, Clear Creek, Sandy River headwaters)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Eagle Creek</strong>: Cold, clear waters east of Gresham hold native cutthroat and rainbow trout; summer dry‑fly hatches are common 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Clear Creek</strong> (tributary of Clackamas): Offers wild trout in rugged, quieter conditions
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Sandy River headwaters</strong> above Marmot/Mt. Hood support trout (small spinners, nymphs, dry flies)&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. Clackamas River Tributaries (Oak Grove Fork, Timothy Lake)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oak Grove Fork</strong>: Nearby, contains brook, rainbow, cutthroat, and brown trout; fly and lure only 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Timothy Lake</strong>: Up on the Clackamas, stocked with rainbows and holds wild cutthroat, browns, and brookies
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>6. Nearby Reservoirs &amp; Ponds (Hartman Pond, Hagg Lake)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Hartman Pond</strong> (Benson State Park): Seasonal trout stocking in spring, plus panfish and catfish 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Henry Hagg Lake</strong> (~45 min away): Heavily stocked in spring and often again in fall; also holds wild cutthroat, brook, and brown trout&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Best Times To Fish
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Spring (Mar–May)</strong>: Peak stocking season; hatchery rainbows in ponds (+ creeks cooling off) 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Summer (Jun–Aug)</strong>: Creeks like Eagle &amp; Clear shine in early morning/evenings. Lakes slow midday
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fall (Sept–Nov)</strong>: Fall plants and natural feed spur activity in lakes &amp; ponds; creeks offer excellent wild trout action
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Winter (Dec–Feb)</strong>: Urban lakes remain fishable after stocking; stream fishing slows down&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
