<h2>
    Licensing, Regulations &amp; Tips
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oregon fishing license</strong> required for anglers 12+, catch limits generally 5 trout/day in stocked waters 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fly-only/barbless hooks</strong> in sections of Eagle Creek and Oak Grove Fork 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Mt. Hood Pond rules</strong>: Youth-only April–August, open to all in fall/winter 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Walmer Willamette/Clackamas tributaries rules check</strong> at ODFW weekly report&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Summary
</h2>
<p>
    <strong>Best local for easy access &amp; quick action:</strong>
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <i>Mt. Hood Pond</i> (stocked, youth season considerations)
    </li>
    <li>
        <i>Salish Ponds &amp; Blue Lake</i> (family-friendly, paved access)
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    <strong>Best for wild trout &amp; scenic fishing:</strong>
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <i>Eagle Creek</i> and <i>Clear Creek</i> (good cutthroat/rainbow opportunities)
    </li>
    <li>
        <i>Oak Grove Fork Clackamas</i> &amp; <i>Timothy Lake</i> (diverse species)
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    <strong>For a full-day adventure:</strong>
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <i>Henry Hagg Lake</i> and <i>Hartman Pond</i> offer diverse species and open water opportunities in spring/fall.
    </li>
</ul>

